Parliament did not ratify the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament rejected, as part of an amendment to the criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph concerning the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the head of the opposition.
MEPs rejected in second reading the draft amendment aimed at reducing penalties for economic crimes, which could have opened the door to freedom for the former prime minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having concluded an a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not final and the court must rule on the convicted woman's appeal in December.
Tymosenko called the regime's political revenge verdict and provoked a process of suspicion of the court's bias in the west as well.
The draft annulment of paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 Members of Parliament.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
