Feeding an obese child: does not take breakfast and takes charcuterie for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, 9% of schoolchildren have an above-average weight and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families who have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This once again shows how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the patterns that surround him is.
On the tables of obese children, for example, sausages are found 50% more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner, according to the survey conducted with an awareness-raising action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In families of young adults, sport is also not a habit, which is now the case with most schoolchildren today - only 15% responded that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
A survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
It was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by the General Health Insurance and the Unilever company.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 pupils from sixth to third grade have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that cause a dramatic increase in the number of overweight, or even obese, children is the absence of proper nutrition and not enough physical exercise.
“Only half of the children surveyed indicated, for example, eating breakfast five times a day – in case of lunch – snacking – dinner, which is one of the basic principles of a good diet,” one of the results of the survey said.
Without breakfast and charcuterie at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development you need some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of students’ families eat at the same time.
In most families, each person eats breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that has been found is that one-tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that families of obese children are more likely to consume unhealthy fries.
Almost every student – not to mention weight – drinks sweet drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of children surveyed do sports regularly but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Prepare your food.
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diets based on the possibilities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating."
Among their favorite dishes are a lot of cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is a high preference for sugary lemonades," the study said.
For lunch it was the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
The children did not want starches at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Towards health
The survey also showed that children are willing to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"In a control of a group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the awareness session 'Obesity is not a coincidence', there was a strong desire to move towards a healthy diet," the survey results indicate.
The most striking was, for example, when it came to sweet lemonades as children began to give preference to drinking water.
The children most often checked the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce the sweet dishes and the "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread flour balls or potatoes).
