History of a brand:
IBM Innovator Begins the Second Century of Its Existence
If someone were to look for the vocabulary that expresses IBM’s strategy as closely as possible, the closest one would be “long-term.”
For a wide audience IBM is the symbol of the technological revolution, is a firm felt as very current and yet since its creation it has been a hundred years.
The foundation of this long-term strategy was laid by the firm’s first leader, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He left this slogan that a large number of global problems can be solved as long as people are willing to think.
Its slogan "THINK!" became the imprint around which the life of a giant future will develop (and also the title of the internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
It was the foundation of the company’s carefully crafted culture by Watson.
For us IBM means a long-term thinking of continuous movements towards the future.
IBM has survived a hundred years thanks to the fact that it has always remained faithful to its core values and yet has not been afraid to change everyone else around it.
This has enabled us in our first century to transform technology, business and society.
We hope that in the second century we will achieve even more"said the current director of the company Samuel J. Palmisano for the anniversary.
A well-prepared system
Watson, in the 1930s, took care of his employees like Bata in the Czech Republic - IBM people were the only ones among the first American employees to have paid vacations, an employer-paid insurance plus a stylish employee uniform and a well-developed system of rewards for inventing them.
In the same way, IBM has a well-developed customer relationship system.
The company was brilliant at the beginning in discovering talent—as one of the first firms to abolish all forms of discrimination and thus have a choice.
The current plan is completely in the spirit of the anti-discrimination strategy as it will be a woman – Virginia Rometty – who should replace Palmisano at the head of IBM.
She has worked at IBM for 30 years and currently holds the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
IBM in recent years has been doing what is called jammy, brain-storming online, from which many future strategies and innovations have emerged.
No wonder he has a lot of ideas - in the firm there are nearly 500,000 people working.
