IBM History: From slices of cheese to flights into the cosmos.
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it was originally called Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - originally it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They possessed technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 chaired the company's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
The leader then cast a shadow on the founder of the firm - it is on Watson's ideas that the company's identity and culture have so far rested.
Watson headed the firm in 1952.
IBM, as its name implies, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
During the first four years of Watson's tenure, revenue increased to $9 million and the firm began to expand in all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable for the firm that after 40 years of management it was his son who occupied the chair of the director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and IBM computers helped NASA guide flights into the cosmos—on Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the flight to the Moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the company of Consulting Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has succeeded at IBM over the past three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet".
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
As far as the field of commerce is concerned, IBM recently developed a “Smarter Commerce” platform that helps merchants manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history on our territory as well.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central for Central and Eastern Europe is headquartered in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team that takes care of speech recognition.
