How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at the time offered travel mainly in the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a penchant for the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however, you had to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good acquaintance" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency agreement that was the condition for traveling to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable, however, and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were consequently many country houses and chalets that the Czechs bought themselves and this habit persists until now.
The travels of the Czechs have been a great revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their peak, the Czechs spent 4 million days of holidays abroad last year in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in Western neighbouring countries has caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, the travel agencies made the Czechs sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at this time to take with you your own canned food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the exchangeability of the Czech crown which allowed our tourists finally after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average salary increased, which caused another important moment around 1997.
Due to increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have started to prepare tours with air charter connections since 1997, which through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what existed before.
At the end of the 1990s the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world apart from the U.S. which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to the distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit the exotic countries each year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully rank in the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holiday abroad including the accompanying charges.
