The Personal Massacre
Peter Englund’s new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a long list of characters that holds your heart.
One tip to get started: carefully tear this page and make it your bookmark.
In this novel by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, as one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the fogs of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book which he accurately describes as "an anti-history work."
It features some well-known names, important treatises or famous battles; there is hardly any ambassador or discussion of strategies and material.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like". We find "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and Sorrow" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, to doctors, ambulances and vendors.
Some of them will become heroes.
Some of the prisoners of war will lose members, go mad, or lose their lives.
Their lives here swing like the candles of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are lit.
The book by Peter Englund deviates from traditional history books.
It brings a denial to the idea that World War I is summed up only by the terrible trench war on the Western front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skillfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are found under hives; one passes Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the tsé-tsé flies are an untreatable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people such a natural disaster, such a hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordita.
When gunshots resonate in the distance, and you are a home mom, do you stay or run away?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, not even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, “the lack of facts has been compounded by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors.”
"Beauty and Grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor of the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
