After this summer’s tragedy, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy... Log in to Facebook.
“We realized it wasn’t that hard to find them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a report recently released by DEMOS’s think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they’re looking for with scientific accuracy — the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team discovered that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. She targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to answer a survey. The questions asked concerned their level of education, their optimism towards their own violence, their coming attitudes towards their own
By getting in touch with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without leaving the office.
“It’s a new way of doing research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not at all surprising: the online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens.”
The study of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook has become the new must-have tool in the hands of scientists.
Reflection groups, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that touch on health issues such as social trends, thanks to "Likes", wall publications and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three contents per day, the “data supernova” generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research papers whose site name appears in the title by nearly 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people that you might not be able to approach on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to investigate people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You were supposed to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you in,” says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information."
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social issues.
According to a recent study by D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and her colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their drunkenness exploits were much more likely to be alcoholic than discreet students about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to possibly help a student whose status would all too often speak of alcohol.
“You can’t treat a problem if you don’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would otherwise not be recognized."
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The site's data team studied statistics on the love situation and Valentine's Day, the 2010 midterm election turnout rate, and a national happiness index (thanks to only available information - the digital freedom champions have long argued that the site could make its data treasury available for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of a survey they haven’t even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect information differently than through the Internet, there is something else online.
"I don't think a lot of users have ever thought about whether a researcher can study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, according to a 2006 study he conducted by observing his students' Facebook walls.
"As far as they know, the exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study will be completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user’s wall.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two totally different things,” says Neil Selwyn.
That’s why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notepad and a pen remain the best tools you can use.
“Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people,” he says.
“Social studies are supposed to address the social aspect – and social is not in front of a computer.”
