7 Lessons from Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview at the Movies This Week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished by the technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans can find most revealing in a recently found Steve Jobs interview that will air this week in the first part of a major market movie is how much that creative spirit had understood the processes and workflow of the products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified himself with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as an organigram enhancer - a man who believed that many business executives suffered from a "disease making them think that a brilliant idea makes an exaggerated amount of manual work...
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Nerds". This series traces the birth of the computer, and he sat for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
By that time, it had been about 10 years since Steve Jobs had had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in transport.
It was only after Steve Jobs’ death that a full video was found in the director’s garage.
This video, slightly backed up, is the basis of the 68-minute film titled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will air in theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about exposing technology philosophies and his business strategies.
Incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide a precise answer.
There are also moments when Steve Jobs’ perfectionism resurfaces, when he seems eager to hear Cringely’s questions, giving him the elbows to accelerate and move on to more important questions or topics.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, Lost Interview is an oddly prescient look. Steve Jobs assesses what he sees as good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous assessments of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then implements them.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences of Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
“Throughout all these years, I’ve always asked, ‘Why are you doing things?’ and the answers are constantly the same: ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs continues to provide details on his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed about how costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" assessed at face value, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured the accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a tour to the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the anecdote of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack phone networks and call for free over long distances.
The device has been the subject of many writings in advance, but Steve Jobs' euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
“We wrapped the ball of different things half a dozen times and you were yelling at the public phone and it happened to you a minute later at the public phone next door,” Jobs says, laughing.
“We were young and, thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves capable of controlling billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We didn't know much, but we invented a little thing that could control big things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs continues by telling a wonderful tour that he and Wozniak have come up with: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night pretending to be Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go crazy laughing just before the Pope himself wakes up.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett’s departure):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he searches for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and gives him a wire.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my definition of a company and the way employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of HP's employees visiting the company's research laboratories, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first ever designed desktop."
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode tube, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On Improving Innovation:
At several points in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products at a glance.
At the beginning of his career, as he settles down to sell some printed circuit boards, a client asks him to assemble a complete computer.
Working with only 30 credit days, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big arguments... they yelled at me saying it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and went to a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that turned out to be incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are breathing a sigh:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industrial leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
“Let’s say you worked at IBM or Xerox, do you make a better copy or a better printer, and then?”
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company does not meet more success.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [it’s these types of people] who end up leading companies and product staff are pushed away from decision-making.
The product engineering that led to this position of monopoly is completely rotten by people who can't imagine designing a good product versus a bad product - the required manual labor.
This is what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took defeat to victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
“A huge amount of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises to make...Some things you can’t do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (those concepts) by putting them together.
Finally, decisions are made by personal taste. It is about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring those things to the product you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists fly.
We are always ashamed to steal great ideas.
That's partly what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who just turned out to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it were not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
