How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines indicates how ubiquitous deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
The administrators of Penn State have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner has taken the stand for a fool by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of violating funding for campaigns related to coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of those who have lived history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton sparked by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The tales of cheating at school and university tests are legion.
There have been instances where teachers gave test responses to students in order to get a good look at their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How many deceptions do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to shout out, "I got you," deception detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research in such psychologies, in particular, psychologies.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been demystified.
The liars look you in the eye.
They don’t sneeze, blush, or always stir.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the statement structure, facial microexpressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and still emerging knowledge about deception, and it is clear that deception detection is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful to navigate in our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are able to read others well, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies "centered on themselves" while women say more lies "centered on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people tend to be introverted.
We also know that if you are perceived as an unbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is what is known as "setting the benchmark data."
This helps to provide a benchmark for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe your subject’s posture, laughter, and voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally shakes their feet constantly so as not to make unfair accusations when you see them shake their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal and nonverbal misconduct.
Consider these clues as red flags, not proof of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or present a “post-interview” relief – an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Questioners often falsely indicate that the interview is finished just to seek to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson slipped away using the past while claiming his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use distant language: “I have not had sexual intercourse with this woman...Mrs. Lewinsky” or completely repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to be honest... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the response perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
