This is an excerpt from the conversation, the complete transcription of which can be found in La Nación on the Internet.
For its Costa Rican fans, the fact that Pearl Jam will perform in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are living?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once for the holidays; it's such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So it makes us excited to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is some kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity in the days before.
What is your message to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us all these years.
It took 21 years for us to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time has passed until this concert.
Some people have already said that their concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve offered over the past 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We have given two gigantic shows in Sao Paolo and we hope this has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to producing there.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; that’s how we learned it, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you offered huge shows, with a lot of songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we have never been there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to perform two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's the point of this?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can perform more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, which is why it’s very difficult to choose which songs to perform every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played in a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of why we love those songs and what we may have forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it is also becoming more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve accomplished?
Yes, absolutely.
“First of all, I don’t think any of us imagined that we were going to form a big rock band, and the fact that we’ve been doing it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together is very emotional.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world where we have always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group of great groups.
We are very friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much stranger when five or ten groups leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to be still friends with all of them and it’s an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that emerged.
It is also very strange that a group like yours stays united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that is much longer than many bands normally last.
Firstly, I think we are all lucky to be still alive, and secondly, we all care about each other.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t go any better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
