The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) said the results highlighted on the accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and seven others lost their lives indicate that the helicopter crashed directly into the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, mentioned that before the aircraft took off, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"The elements that appear to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met the necessary requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations made in the impact area do not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
"In a search it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact was presented in a structural way.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The ground had a slope of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
For now, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as soon as possible; but the investigation can take a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that at the time of impact, the Presidential Staff helicopter was operating at cruising speed and this took place on an ascending soft ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact," he says.
During the press conference, TBS holder Pérez Jácome listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in the AICM mentioned adequate conditions for takeoff, and as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were low-altitude cloud layers.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew sought a lower altitude area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was neither loss of control nor alteration of the flight trajectory.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information available to date makes it possible to assume that the impact occurred on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The model of dispersion of the aircraft remains makes it possible to assume that the helicopter collided with the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No traces of fire or explosion have been detected:
In the site of the accident there is always no trace in the remains of the aircraft of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above average sea level, the ground had a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he may have disarticulated during his journey.
The information provides evidence that appears to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful search in a larger area than the surrounding area, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, which supports the assumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security leads investigation to discover obesity gene in children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Child and Adolescent Obesity Genetics' protocol that will allow for the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the 20th Century National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites the rightful and ineligible population to present themselves to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the evidence to minors is carried out every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol started in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sporting Unit Independencia (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Sporting Unit Morelos (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires related to nutrition.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays it will be applied to all participants of the anthropometric measurements (weight, size, circumference of size), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (it is sought to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López noted that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
“The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 reported that in just six years there was a 77 percent increase in obesity in boys and 47 percent in girls, and a dramatic increase in overweight,” said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent Indo-American inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the complete assessment of the children, which allows to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
It even says that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is handled in a confidential manner, doctors hand it over in writing to parents, who are explained each of the measures and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying sitting in front of the TV most of the day and using means of transportation instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, that is, the highest consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - meat paste with cornmeal wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins in this protocol and genetic analysis.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid crazies
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a blend with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200,000 cassis every rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the pavement was complete, even the pavement would be reduced.
During his conference A Technological Opinion on Cassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some northern cities of the country, to improve the yield, and therefore, the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltens, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthens, which together give the pavement its characteristic screw.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of nearly 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt-jouta becomes breaking, a-jouta-
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental and temperature conditions, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City in their majority were covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and later compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he says, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating efforts, it allows the forces to propagate very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, these would spread better, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, one puts a last layer called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the bearing layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be cared for.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil becomes wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes bruises.
In the process of formation of a cassis, he says, the first that spoils is the rolling film and only later the asphalt layer is affected, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that needs to be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for breakage formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent breakage formation.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair cassis easily and without having to use high temperatures.
