So was the work of the person of Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A dactyloscopist from Cali has gone down in history as the man who confirmed the death of Alfonso Cano.
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4, a dactylographer at the CTI in Cali went down in history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme head of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprinters working in the CTI’s local offices, this week it was the turn of “availability” of Eliazar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has been working in the field of forensic investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In the year 2000 he moved to the capital of Valle and after following proper courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliasar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big awaited him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be the man who led the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the map with Guillermo León Sáenz's ten fingerprints (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigative team at the site of the body, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant from the area, without glasses and much leaner.
But the fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galton magnifying glass, ink, a pickup and a lantern, Eliasar compared the body’s fingerprints with those on the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that, yes, he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
In Search of the Footprint
For a dactylographer from Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos gave to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don’t know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without margin of error, which can be crucial in resolving crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, fingerprinters support investigations for crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present false ID cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher told that in a case of theft he had to remove part of the wall of a house, because in this place the thief had pressed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to take a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in different thefts," he recalls.
Fingerprints can also dismiss or confirm suspects in cases of homicide.
Recently we found a dead man, with bottles of drink around him.
In the course of the investigation, it was determined that a parent may be suspected of the crime and that a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if that doesn't guarantee he's the killer, it puts him on the scene of the crime.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that “fingerprints are being extracted from objects with chemical or physical reagents.”
When they appear, a picker or tape is used to pick them up.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the delinquent database, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of undocumented Colombians," said the CTI expert.
He explained that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
As everything that shines is not gold, everything you touch does not necessarily become an imprint.
However, it can be used if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
