Japan Rescued After Earthquake
GDP rises 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still recovering after the devastating earthquake that has become the nuclear crisis, Japan’s worst disaster since World War II.
The first estimates by the Government of Tokyo estimated the material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have eased.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, Gross Domestic Product data between July and September served to definitively turn the page: GDP rose 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% at an annualized rate.
In addition, the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - assumes the highest rate of growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% drop in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted growth.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that calls for taking advantage of the crisis to consolidate – or rebuild – infrastructure, use deficiencies to grow from zero.
Japan has woken up mainly due to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the domestic market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refugee values" chosen by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the eurozone and the turmoil of U.S. forecasts, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of major tech groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, blamed their weak results between July and September for the yen’s contribution.
While markets continue to be headquartered in peripheral EU countries, the Yoshihiko Noda Government is not shrinking its guard.
"We need to monitor the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said Motohisa Furukawa, Secretary of State for Economic Policy.
And indeed, the prospects are not at all encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) noted that the majority of member countries presented clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points of the global economy has highlighted that the main powers are being held back.
