As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent book synthesizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among the countries that the growth of migrants is positive, and there is a strong consensus among the experts on immigration.
Restrict immigration anemic growth and detrimental to employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they are likely to substitute for national workers, particularly low-skilled workers, who are exerting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, practicing mostly occupations in sectors that are deprived of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow job offer.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on nationals' salaries and employment.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% of real long-term wages.
And that without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a large proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
