According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers are of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who has spent a long time in Maiduguri, a northern Nigerian city, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who says he is close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is a step forward, but we probably have to wait for more formal evidence before we talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“It has been known for years that the sect has received outside financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "supports" have become increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or its operating modes, which now involve the use of kamikazes or explosive devices that are increasingly complex and of the same bill as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has therefore pressed Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of illuminated people of little interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means in haoussa "Western education is a sin" - advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes itself and demands strict respect for Sharia law while its activists engage in the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are primarily aimed at churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active, multiplying attacks on police stations.
Abuja's reaction is, as usual, without nuances.
The army is invading the city, 800 people are dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, is killed in prison.
From then on the sect will radicalize and leave its fiefs of the north.
Last Christmas, she claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos, then another in Abuja.
In June, it was again in Abuja that Boko Haram took over the secure police headquarters during a suicide attack, its first.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that would navigate from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria is now of concern to all security specialists.
While Aqmi has invested Mali and Niger, which the al-Shebab Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat in the heart of the continent.
Last week, during an interview in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was ready to "share all the information".
The world according to Republican presidential candidates
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry rival simplicity and ignorance.
Can an America weakened by the crisis manage a complex world with simple, even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe it.
For the past few days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and others have been multiplying staggering statements and shortcuts in foreign policy, traditionally a Republican strongpoint.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, slogans – often unsupported – fuse.
Mitt Romney, the best-placed in the race for the “Great Old Party” nomination, threatened to drag the Chinese before the WTO and question them “for manipulating their currency,” a theme in an America exasperated by the migration of entire chunks of his industry to Asia.
So bad if it must involve the initiation of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama's former ambassador to China and the only candidate to have a sophisticated foreign policy vision, almost strangled himself in the face of an attitude that "flatters" emotions.
He called for a muscular but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama’s current position).
But Huntsman, who stagnates in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
In the image of Reagan
Romney has also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to stop its nuclear program.
“If I’m elected, I’ll stop Iran,” he bragged.
“If Obama is re-elected, they’ll have the bomb.”
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing to fulfill his obligations to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second best-placed candidate, has an embarrassing disregard for the files.
Recently, he called for countering the Chinese military threat because Beijing is “trying to develop a nuclear capability” – apparently ignorant of the fact that China has held the military atom since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants strikes against Iran, says he is ready to engage the U.S. military in Mexico against drug cartels.
The use of torture against alleged terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
We are far from the 2008 Republican candidate, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
Opponents of the current president respond that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to put water in his wine in the matter of counter-terrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, on the too hasty departure of Iraq’s “boys”, on his tergiversations in Libya, thus sticking a weak label to him.
But the attack is not so easy.
The population considers Obama’s national security record, which eliminated bin Laden, rather positive.
Since Iraq, she has been wary of military interventions that lead to enslavement.
And, by arguing that America needs to be rebuilt economically to resurrect its leadership, Obama strikes more justly.
The Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe to Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part, on Tuesday, on the Baltic shores, between orchestra and fine buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia to Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the steering wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe each year through a first tube of 1,224 km connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second tube is due to be completed by the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site seems to be a victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But this is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in achieving its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, highly gas-consuming Western countries, whose deposits are declining.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us in an organic way,” Fillon confirmed when inaugurating the pipeline, demonstrating how big gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-clad steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"A hundred must have been abducted or destroyed, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply the measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project officials gave up on it while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state company permanently set up off their coasts.
"In the event of a breakdown, we will stop the gas passing in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who have predicted welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide of one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of traveling at a speed of 3 meters per second, he delivers accurate information about possible metal deformations.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The flow of gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 bars at the arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty renewable years, the entire capacity of gas transport.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure to get back into their expenses, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the exit door for the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specifics of the gas that arrives, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a fragrance of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of design but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine gave the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the twentieth century ", says Maria Sebregondi, who has become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million coins.
We are far from the confidential production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a robotic portrait of the buyer, because the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its beginnings, now has almost 100 employees and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her bookshelves in bookshops, from the Fnac to small downtown shops, and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agenda, pens, computer covers... The brand stands out on a whole range of supports.
A success that has made enviable: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a voluntary public policy in 2005, the unemployment rate of people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the general population.
Disheartening?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, managing director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of people with disabilities.
" The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, there is still a great deal to be done."
It must be said that for unemployed people with disabilities, many obstacles remain before access to employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree and out of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very prevalent: 53% for people with disabilities, compared with 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that complicate the return to employment, and that "constitute the knot of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, Managing Director of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit workers with disabilities.
This is for objective brakes.
There remains the unsaid, the mentalities that are evolving, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise for the City association indicated that the managers surveyed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with an "overrepresentation of wheelchair users, mentally or intellectually disabled".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of 1987.
The latest known figures, dating from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed" institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also translates into real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ workers with disabilities, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
